git push -u origin main

# Environment Variables

Approach 1: Add them to the Expo Dashboard (Recommended)Expo expects you to link variables to specific environments (development, preview, production) directly on their servers.

- Go to Expo.dev, log in, and click on your project.
- In the left-hand sidebar, click on Environment Variables.
- Click Create Variable.
- Set the Name (e.g., EXPO_PUBLIC_API_URL), the Value, select development under the Environment tags, and choose Plain text or Sensitive as the visibility.
- Save it, and re-run your eas build command. The warning will disappear, and the variables will be injected properly.

Approach 2: Push your local .env via the CLI

# This securely pushes your local keys to your EAS project's development profile

> eas env:create --environment development --visibility plaintext
> eas env:create --environment development,preview,production --visibility plaintext

```bash
{
  "build": {
    "development": {
      "developmentClient": true,
      "environment": "development"
    },
    "preview": {
      "distribution": "internal",
      "environment": "preview"
    },
    "production": {
      "environment": "production"
    }
  }
}

```

Approach 3: Tell EAS to look for your local files (Fastest bypass)

- You can create a .easignore file in your root folder and make sure it does not include your .env files, allowing EAS to upload them securely just for the build runner.

# Note

Never prefix absolute backend master secrets (like a Stripe Secret Key or AWS Private Key) with EXPO*PUBLIC*.

```bash
Private Policy
https://app-privacy-policy-generator.firebaseapp.com/
```
